reviewText: if you audit the course, practice software is unavailable and you can't take the tests. I was an ArcGIS professional for years, and just wanted to brush up on my skills.
Great content, excellent instruction, frustrating/arbitrary quiz grading non-system.  "Help" reps were unwilling or unable to resolve/explain.

Well structured with clear instructions and great material. However, much like the previous courses in the GIS specialization, there is a very heavy focus on ArcGIS - so much so that this course might as well be called "how to run geospatial analyses in ArcGIS."While it's all very interesting, I was hoping this course would go more in-depth into the various analysis tools in ArcGIS that are introduced and how they work behind the scenes. I understand we need an application in which to work with the GIS concepts but the course has entire modules that focus specifically on ArcGIS-specific functionality (such as creating reports and customizing colour ramps)

While I thought the last two classes were superb, this one was a slow drag. The final project gave me a lot of trouble, and judging by the forums, it was challenging for a lot of other people as well. The problem for a lot of people is that once you start doing something incorrectly, its hard to correct it. Getting help could take days, and even though there's no hard deadline, I submitted my project late because I felt as if I had exhausted my options within the week long timeline. The grading system (which might be a site-wide problem), is shoddy. I knew when I submitted my project that it was not worth full credit. Even so, I got full credit from the graders. They didn't even bother reading the grading rubric.
The main assignment was extremely hard. I think a little too hard relative to what we had learned up to that point.
Peer review is not best way to grade if requires some form of subjective judgement from people that maybe are not the very qualified to provide it.

This class had a lot of good material and it truly showed how powerful GIS is in analysis.  My recommendation would be for this class to be broken into two sessions to really practice everything that was taught in the videos.  However, I plan on doing this on my own through the GIS help boxes before I take the 4th class.
The final assignment instructions should be more clear. I was not able to get the exact same statistics as the example and struggled for days to match it.

This was a great course and I learned so much. Nick Santos is an excellent teacher. My only issue was that there was no way to find out what I did wrong on the final project. I tried other students' solutions, but they didn't work. It would be great to have an extra video after completion to see the instructor work through the final project.
Please update the course with ArcGis Pro. It would be good if the certificate contains the following info also: Duration: 4 weeks  and Garde Achieved: x%ArcGis A bit details about the course.
It would be better if you explain step by step , why is what for this Assignment.

This course gives good and many examples of various geoprocessing tools but goes through them a little quick in my opinion. I personally would enjoy some more examples of when you would use such a tool in your workflow.

I taught myself GIS using QGIS with various online resources. I took this course to have my first structured training on GIS and to be familiar with ArcMap. Now, I'm making maps on the side using ArcMap. The course is fairly easy if you already have experience with GIS. The additional exercises are really helpful too. One con is that there are times that despite doing 100% everything on the video, you end up with a different result. It's a pro in a way that it helps you troubleshoot GIS issues. Also, props to Nick (instructor) for replying both on the discussion page and my email about some missing data. He is also a clear and direct speaker and explains the nuances of doing this and that. Worth the payment!

This course offered a step by step approach to a GIS workflow, from sourcing and cleaning data, to performing initial analysis to subset data, and getting an end result which was then made into a n appropriately presented and published map. This course went into some more advanced concepts than the intro course, and I found most of the assignments useful for developing an understanding. There was a lot of ground to cover, and at times I was frustrated and lost, but ultimately that's the nature of the beast.The final assignment was a good amalgamation of the skills used in the course, though many people had issues with the assets provided. Whether the issues were intentional or not, I'm not sure.
Good course, could have been more explanatory.

Thanks!

It is an excellent course; you easily notice that the people involved (especially Nick) have put a lot of effort to prepare a high level course (excellent lectures, and a great selection of topics, materials and assignments). Compare to the two previous courses, this one is harder; one covers a lot of topics. You have to give yourself plenty of time to watch the videos (take notes and go through the materials), and I personally think that there is no way you can complete the assignments in the time they suggest. The language of the questions in the Quizzes was bit confusing.

This course adds more knowledge to that covered in the previous courses in the specialization, but its organization could use some improvement. Some of the material was intended to increase the student's understanding of topics covered in the previous courses, but these sections often repeated information from the previous courses without giving enough new material or presenting the new material in an organized manner. This does mean students with prior GIS experience might find this class helpful on its own without taking the prior classes, though. The exercises provided are good practice, but they also repeat a bit too much material from the previous courses at times.

This is the third course I have taken in the UC Davis GIS specialization, and it did not disappoint!  The final project was quite challenging for me, even though I had taken good notes throughout all the courses.  However, when I successfully completed the project, I had a great sense of accomplishment and I am inspired to continue learning GIS.My only comment about the Coursera online course format is that the estimations of time commitment for these GIS courses is WAY TOO LOW.  I hope I am not the only student for whom the coursework typically takes significantly more time than estimated.  The final project in this course was supposed to take 2.5 hours, but I think it took me at least 12 hours!

This course is a wonderful exploration of some of the tools at the disposal of a GIS practitioner.  Nick provided wonderful applicable examples and did a great job clearly explaining the process of doing, and the processes behind doing many of the geospatial analysis functions available through Arc GIS.  The only issue with the class was the use of Arc Desktop instead of Arc Pro.  The benefit of this was the value in seeing the stripped down GUI behind the scenes of many of the more user friendly functions of Pro.  However,  with industry standards moving towards Pro, it would have been nice to get more experience on the platform that many of us will probably be using in the field.
